  "prompt": "What are your views about Narendra Modi's decision to stop circulation of 500 and 1000 denomination notes?",
  "response": "The decision to demonetize the 500 and 1,000 rupee notes in India, announced by Prime Minister Narendra Modi on November 8, 2016, was a significant and controversial economic measure. The primary objectives cited by the government for this move included curbing black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption, as well as promoting a digital economy.\n\nSupporters of the demonetization policy argue that it temporarily disrupted the hoarding of unaccounted wealth and encouraged digital transactions and formalization in the economy. It was seen as a bold step against corruption and illicit financial activities.\n\nCritics, on the other hand, point out several negative consequences. The sudden implementation led to widespread chaos and inconvenience, especially for those in the informal sector and rural areas who rely heavily on cash transactions. The economic disruption also reportedly affected GDP growth and led to job losses in certain sectors.\n\nThe Reserve Bank of India later reported that the majority of the demonetized currency had been deposited back into the banking system, raising questions about the policy's efficacy in rooting out black money. Moreover, the anticipated long-term benefits such as a significant shift to digital transactions and reduction in cash-based corruption have seen mixed results.\n\nOverall, while demonetization was a bold attempt to address systemic issues within the Indian economy, its execution and impact were highly debated, with both tangible benefits and significant challenges.",
